# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sheffield-children-s-hospital
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/2-haymarket] The building was constructed in 1871 to serve as Sheffield's head post office.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/2-haymarket] It was originally intended also to house the local branch of the Inland Revenue, but the space was almost immediately found to be inadequate, and within a couple of months of its opening in 1872, the Revenue moved to offices on Norfolk Street.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/2-haymarket] The building has two stories and an attic and is in the classical revival style, adopting a form which was already old-fashioned at the time it was built.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/2-haymarket] In 1879, it was described as "a fairly handsome Doric structure, but inadequate to the requirements of the rapidly increasing postal and telegraphic business of so large a town".
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/2-haymarket] A further section at the rear of the building, facing Commercial Street, was constructed at the same time and in the same style, but is of a single storey, with a basement below.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/2-haymarket] In 1910, a new head post office for the city was constructed on Fitzalan Square.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/2-haymarket] The building was purchased by the Sheffield Stock Exchange, which opened its new site with a grand ceremony in 1911.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/2-haymarket] The stock exchange operated until 1967, when the creation of British Steel Corporation dramatically reduced its business.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/2-haymarket] The building was restored in the 1970s, and the interior was completely reworked to serve as a branch of the Yorkshire Bank, which it remained until September 2014.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/2-haymarket] As of July 2017, the building remains unoccupied following Yorkshire Bank's vacation of the site.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/2-haymarket] There are currently plans for the refurbishment of 2 Haymarket and the adjacent building at 5-7 Commercial Street, which would include the addition of a second floor on the Commercial Street building and the creation of 11 flats across both buildings.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] The site is a scheduled monument, the works are Grade I listed and the workers' cottages, counting house, and manager's house are Grade II* listed.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] The site was used for iron forging for 500 years, although there is evidence of other metal working before 1200.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] Its early history is intimately tied with the nearby Beauchief Abbey, which operated a smithy (blacksmith's shop) in the vicinity as well as number of mills along the River Sheaf.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] A 1725 map shows that the fields, subsequently flooded to provide the dam at the site, had been called "Sinder Hills", the cinders referring to the waste resulting from prior lead smelting activities in the area in the 16th and early 17th centuries.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] However, the "Abbey Dale Works" as such, the buildings of which now form the Abbeydale Industrial Hamlet, are first formally recorded in 1714 (though it may have derived directly from the "New Wheel" operated by Hugh Stephenson, as detailed in rent books from 1685).
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] From the 17th century onwards, the site primarily operated as a scythe works until, in 1933, it was closed by Tyzak Sons and Turner (tenants since 1849).
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] In 1935 it was bought by the Alderman J.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] Graves Trust, which donated the site to the city.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] The works was briefly reopened during the Second World War to aid in Britain's war effort.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] The Council for the Conservation of Sheffield Antiquities explored and initiated the restoration of Abbeydale Works in 1964.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] They discovered the remains of six buildings in addition to those still standing.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] Following the complete restoration the works were finally opened as a museum in 1970.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] Sheffield City Council closed the museum in 1997 as a cost-cutting measure.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] It was then leased to the Sheffield Industrial Museums Trust who reopened the museum in 1998.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] Abbeydale Industrial Hamlet is run as a working museum, with works and buildings dating from between 1714 and 1876.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] The museum demonstrates the process making blister steel from iron and coke, then refining this steel using techniques that originated with Benjamin Huntsman's invention of the crucible steel process.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] The river provides water power via a water wheel.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] There are several wheels on the site for driving a tilt hammer, for the initial forging of the scythe blades; grinding machinery, which also has steam installed as backup for times of drought, and a set of bellows.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] The blades were also hand forged for finishing.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-industrial-hamlet] The museum is open Thursday to Sunday inclusive during peak season, and entry is free.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] The Abbeydale Picturehouse Bar reopened on 1 December 2022.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] The first film to be shown was *The Call of the Road*.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] The cinema had seating for 1,560 people and also included a ballroom and a billiard hall.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] Cine-variety played a major role at the Abbeydale until 1930 and the arrival of the "talkies" talking films; from this time the stage was used purely to house the sound equipment.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] In the mid-1950s the cinema was purchased by the Star Cinema Group which decorated the entire building and installed new projection and sound equipment, including a wide screen.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] The cinema closed on 5 July 1975 and was subsequently used as an office furniture showroom until 1991.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] In 1989 the building was given a Grade II listing by English Heritage being a good example of an early 1920s mid-sized suburban cinema with both cinema and theatre facilities.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] In 1991 the sprung floor in the ballroom was removed, and local businesses "Abbey Snooker" and "Bar Abbey" occupied the site.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] The Abbeydale Picture House hosted regular performances and fundraisers to raise money towards the ongoing restoration of the building.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] In June 2012 a stage adaptation of Hi-de-Hi! was produced by the picture house in conjunction with the family of the late David Croft.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] The building is open for guided tours as part of the Heritage Open Days program.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] On 30 October 2012 the picture house was sold at auction to Phil Robins, for £150,000 with the intention to renovate the building and bring it back into public use as a climbing and sports centre.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] During this period further renovations were undertaken by Phil Robins, assisted during 2015-16 by Hand Of.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] In January 2017 Abbeydale Picture House was leased to CADS Trust, a Sheffield-based arts charity, who are continuing the restoration project.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] The building is now regularly open to the public as a mixed use community arts venue as work progresses.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/abbeydale-picture-house] In January 2025 Abbeydale Picture House was acquired by True North Brew Co, a Sheffield-based hospitality company and brewery.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] The hospital was planned as far back as 1963 with many sites being optioned including Silsden and also a site nearer to Skipton.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] Building work was initiated in 1966 to a plan by then-renowned, later disgraced architect John Garlick Llewellyn Poulson.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] His later trial had nothing to do with his designs for Airedale Hospital.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] The original estimate for the construction of the 32-acre site was £4.5 million including equipment.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] In 1967, this was revised to £5 million.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] The hospital, with an initial designation of 650 beds, was due to open in 1969, but was eventually opened in stages starting in July 1970, and was officially opened by the Prince of Wales on 11 December of that year.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] Upon opening in July 1970, it was revealed that it would actually house 643 beds and have an eventual cost of £5.4 million.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] The maternity ward opened on 6 July 1970, after the main sections of the hospital, with the first birth being on 7 July 1970.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] The opening of Airedale spelt the end for some of the older hospitals in the area, namely Keighley Victoria, St Johns and Mortons Bank.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] These all closed in 1970 on transfer of patients to the new facility.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] For the first few years of the hospital being open, it had an average employment rota of 1,400 people, making it the largest service employer in the area.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] In 1989, Airedale was the hospital that Tony Bland, the 96th and final Hillsborough disaster victim, was transferred to.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] Mr Bland was in a persistent vegetative state (PVS) after being crushed at Hillsborough.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] His parents successfully applied to the High Court to cease his feeding and allow him to die, which he did on 3 March 1993.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] The hospital was the scene of demonstrations by pro-life campaigners during this time.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] In September 2021, the hospital acquired a British Rail Class 144 "Pacer" train carriage after Airedale Hospital and Community Charity, the official charity for Airedale NHS Foundation Trust, won a competition by the Department for Transport.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] It plans to use the vehicle as a non-clinical communal space.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] As of April 2022, the hospital was said to have "the largest single flat roof" of any English hospital – around 320,000 square feet (30,000 m2) – which reportedly resulted in the "most roof leaks in the country".
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] It is also believed to be the oldest reinforced autoclaved aerated concrete (RAAC) hospital in the UK, which poses a dangerous risk to its overall infrastructure.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] On 25 May 2023 it was announced that the hospital would be rebuilt as it contains significant amounts of RAAC.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/airedale-general-hospital] *The Guardian* newspaper noted that a 2020 proposal to rebuild Airedale Hospital was not funded by HM Treasury during Rishi Sunak's term as Chancellor of the Exchequer, despite a "catastrophic" grade of risk and a warning that an incident was "likely".
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The site was previously occupied by a mansion known as Alder Hey which the local poor law guardians acquired for use as a children's home in 1910.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The mansion was converted for use as a military hospital in 1914.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the First World War, the United States Army established Camp Hospital 40 on the site, operated by Hospital Unit Q and, subsequently, Unit W.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] American sources commonly refer to Alder Hey as being within Liverpool's Knotty Ash area.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the Second World War, parts of the hospital were again used to treat injured military personnel.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The Liverpool Neonatal Surgical Unit opened at the hospital in 1953.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] This unit was the first neonatal intensive care unit in the United Kingdom.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The opening was largely due to the efforts of Isabella Forshall, a paediatric surgeon.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1990 when Myrtle Street Children's Hospital (founded in 1869 and previously known as Royal Liverpool Children's Hospital) closed, Alder Hey absorbed its A&E department.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital authority was one of 57 such bodies which became an NHS hospital trust in 1991.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Ronald McDonald House, a home for the families of sick children, opened in 1993.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1999 an inquiry was instituted into the Alder Hey organs scandal and to investigate the hospital's practices in respect of removal and retention of human tissue.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The inquiry had far-reaching effects throughout the UK hospital system and provided the impetus for the Human Tissue Act 2004.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In August 2008 the Royal Liverpool Children's NHS Trust became an NHS foundation trust and changed its name to Alder Hey NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Between 2010 and 2014 the number of doctors employed at the trust increased from 269 to 344, while the number of managers increased from 70 to 86.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] At the end of March 2017, the trust was confirmed as one of four additional NHS Global Digital Exemplars, joining the twelve announced in September 2016.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey had its centenary year in 2014, the last year in which it operated from the buildings on its original site.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A new hospital was procured under Private Finance Initiative contract in neighbouring Springfield Park.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The works, which were carried out by Laing O'Rourke at a cost of £187 million, began on 26 March 2013 and the hospital opened in October 2015.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It was Europe's first children's hospital built in a park.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The original Alder Hey buildings were mostly demolished and the land was reclaimed as new parkland for the surrounding community.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Features of the new hospital include access to play areas, natural light and striking views of the park are available wherever possible Children and young people were involved with the design of the new hospital.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A drawing of a flower by teenage patient Eleanor Brogan impressed architects and inspired their final design.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is a centre of excellence for oncology and muscular dystrophy as well as spinal, heart and brain conditions.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey has Europe's first 3T Intraoperative MRI scanner which is a pioneering technology for neurosurgery, providing surgeons with extremely high resolution images and reducing the need for repeat operations in 90% of cases.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It currently employs about 2,400 staff and treats over 270,000 children from across the UK each year.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts paediatric research into children's medicines, infection, inflammation and oncology.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It has research partners including the University of Liverpool and is a member of Liverpool Health Partners.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey conducts more than 100 clinical research studies on an ongoing basis, ranging from observation to clinical trials.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The hospital is within the National Institute for Health and Care Research's Top 100 Performing Trust's for participation recruitment in 2013/14.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey was a finalist in the Clinical Research Impact category of the 2013 HSJ Awards and in 2014 the innovation team received the Health Service Journal Award for improving health care with technology.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2016 the first phase of a bespoke research, education and innovation centre, Institute in the Park, opened next to Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In November 2015, the institute hosted a children's health Hackathon in conjunction with Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey Children's Charity supports the work of the hospital.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In addition to NHS funding which covers the running costs of the hospital, Alder Hey relies on charitable support.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Funds are spent directly on initiatives in the hospital to benefit patients.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] It funds research initiatives, patient and family enhancements and state of the art medical equipment.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Known as the 'Imagine Appeal' until 2012, Alder Hey Children's Charity is based within the hospital.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 14 October 2013 the charity launched a public appeal to raise £30m to fund equipment, facilities and research at Alder Hey's new hospital, Alder Hey in the Park.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2015 the charity announced over £20m had been raised.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2009 charitable support allowed Alder Hey to buy Europe's first 3T intraoperative MRI scanner.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In one charitably funded project, the sound recordist and musician Chris Watson was employed to devise an art project, using bird song recordings made by children to calm other young patients as they received injections and other treatments.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 1978, the charity Art For Their Sake, a team of volunteer artists led by founder George Nicholas (now of Ormskirk, England), produced the world's longest mural in the corridors of Alder Hey Children's Hospital.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] A Guinness Record was set with a total of 17,963 square feet of murals, and awarded to the hospital in 1986.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Nicholas and his team continued to work on these murals for a period of 30 years, adding to as well as restoring and maintaining, for a total of over 34,000 square feet.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Alder Hey runs an Arts for Health programme, funded entirely through charitable sources including Alder Hey Children's Charity.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme aims to enhance the experience of being a patient and includes animation projects, music and dance therapy, creative writing, comedy workshops and storytelling.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] An international child health development programme led by Alder Hey clinicians focuses on humanitarian work in developing countries.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme includes provision of immediate medical support, knowledge sharing and involvement with international clinical trials.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] The programme has undertaken work across Africa and Asia, including Pakistan, Malawi, Nepal and India.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] During the 1990s, Alder Hey was featured in the BBC television series *Children's Hospital*.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In 2011, chef Heston Blumenthal took to the challenge of changing the dinner menu of Alder Hey Children's Hospital on his televised show, *Heston's Mission Impossible*.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Since September 2012, Alder Hey has regularly featured on the CBBC television series *Operation Ouch!*.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In October 2013, the Care Quality Commission's Intelligent Monitoring system placed Alder Hey in category one, meaning it would be amongst the first hospitals to be inspected under a new style of inspection.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In May 2014, Alder Hey was inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Requires Improvement.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] In June 2015, Alder Hey was re-inspected by the Care Quality Commission and was given the overall rating Good, and was rated Outstanding in the Caring category.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Another inspection took place in 2018, the overall rating was unchanged.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Dame Josephine Williams was appointed Chair of the Trust Board in February 2019.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] Louise Shepherd CBE was appointed Chief Executive of the trust in March 2008.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alder-hey-children-s-hospital] On 26 January 2023, the Alder Hey Children's Hospital NHS Foundation Trust was granted the Honorary Freedom of the Metropolitan Borough of Sefton.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alfred-bean-hospital] The facility has its origins in the Driffield Cottage Hospital on Bridlington Road which was completed in 1873.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alfred-bean-hospital] When the cottage hospital became rather decrepit, a new facility, entirely funded by Alfred Bean, a local businessman, was commissioned.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alfred-bean-hospital] It was built further east along the Bridlington Road and was completed in 1931.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/alfred-bean-hospital] It joined the National Health Service in 1948 and, after the East Riding General Hospital closed in 1990, the Alfred Bean Hospital became the main hospital in the area.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] The **Sheffield Children's Hospital** is a healthcare facility for children in Broomhill, Sheffield, South Yorkshire, England.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] It is managed by the Sheffield Children's NHS Foundation Trust.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] The hospital first opened on 15 November 1876 as a children's infirmary in Brightmore House, on Brook Hill in Sheffield.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] Two years later it moved to its current site on Western Bank where it was accommodated in a pair of semi-detached houses.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] By the mid 1890s it was decided that the two old house were inadequate and should be pulled down and replaced.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] A new building on Brook Hill was opened in 1903, designed by the architect John Dodsley Webster.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] The first X-ray machine and electric lights arrived in 1907 and a new operating theatre and electric radiators were installed in the 1920s.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] Two new wards were completed in 1927, a baby ward was opened in the 1930s and a second operating theatre was built in the 1950s.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] The accident and emergency department was extended in the 1970s and services were transferred from the Northern General Hospital in the 1990s.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] During the 1990s it was featured in the BBC Television series *Children's Hospital*.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] Local football club Sheffield Wednesday donated their shirt sponsorship to Sheffield Children's Hospital and the associated Children's Hospital Charity for the 2009–10 and 2010–11 seasons.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] A new wing, built at a cost of £40 million, was completed in 2018.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] The new wing provides a new hospital main entrance, outpatients consulting suites, specialist diagnostic and treatment areas, and three new wards.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] The new wing was officially opened by Prince Harry in July 2019.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] The Sheffield Children's Clinical Research Facility (CCRF) opened in 2008 as the first dedicated CCRF in the UK.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] Research at Sheffield Children's NHS Foundation Trust spans a range of specialities including bone disease, genetics, respiratory disease, neurology, radiology, cancer and blood diseases, endocrinology and mental health.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] In 2012 the hospital received over £1 million in grants for research into the treatment of bronchiolitis, the use of vibration plate therapy to prevent fractures in children, and the development of bone scanning to replace X-rays in the study of bones in children.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] The hospital is served by University of Sheffield tram stop which is situated a short walk away on the South Yorkshire Supertram network.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] The stop was opened in 1995 and is served by the Blue and Yellow routes.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] Local bus services stop on the main road, Western Bank, in front of the hospital.
[src:sheffield-children-s-hospital/sheffield-children-s-hospital] Additionally, a bus stop within the grounds of the adjacent Royal Hallamshire Hospital acts as the terminus of the *H1* bus service which runs across the city to the Northern General Hospital, providing free transport for NHS staff between the hospitals of Sheffield.
